node.text: Vive la resistance! 🇫🇷 Join me 600m below Paris to liberate the city in a special new “Don’t be a Tourist” episode with @Microsoft 🕵🏻‍♀️Discover a WWII bunker deserted for decades and relive the liberation of Paris with HoloLens mixed reality technology through the eyes of French resistance fighters in the underworld. [Ad] Proud to be working with #Microsoft again to keep history alive 💪#HoloLens #Paris #History 🎞 For the full widescreen viewing experience, head to MessyNessyChic.com (link in da bio) or check out the "Don’t be a Tourist" web series on our Youtube channel 📺

node.text:
If you were a beachgoer in Georgian or Victorian times, more specifically, a female beachgoer, your day at the seaside would’ve likely had all the fun sucked out of it by a little invention known as the bathing machine. 

Introduced in the 1750s when proper swimwear hadn’t yet been invented, the bathing machine was all about upholding those crazy rules of bathing etiquette which kept women & their beach bodies out of sight (while the men frolicked freely on the beach, of course). The wooden carts with two doors on either sides allowed bathers to change out of their clothes and into their bathing suits without having to be seen by the opposite sex walking across the beach in ‘improper clothing’, which in those days, on the gender-segregated beaches of Europe, would have been the ultimate walk of shame. The four-wheeled box would be rolled out to sea, usually by horse or sometimes human power & hauled back in when the beachgoer signalled to the driver by raising a small flag attached to the roof. Some models were equipped with a canvas tent lowered from the seaside door, giving the bather greater privacy. 

Once deep enough in the surf, our bather would then exit the cart using the door facing away from prying eyes on the beach and proceed to paddle. For inexperienced swimmers (which would have been most Victorian women in their billowing swimwear), some beach resorts offered the service of a “dipper”, a strong person of the same sex who would escort the bather out to sea in the cart and essentially push them into the water and yank them out when they were done. As long you as you didn’t drown, for the average Victorian, this sobering experience could be considered a successful day at the beach. 

Some of the bathing machines have indeed survived to this day as beach huts. Those adorably photogenic and colourful little beach houses? They’re direct successors of the Georgian bathing machine! When they were no longer needed for being carted out to sea, many were simply stripped of their wheels and plonked permanently back on the beach; a little-known reminder of eccentric seaside history.

Find more curious stories on www.MessyNessyChic.com

node.text: Someone (definitely not my husband 🙃) told me I shouldn’t paint stripes in this room because the walls were too textured and the paint would leak through the tape. Being the stubborn little Capricorn that I am, I went and found a hack for these perfect, glorious stripes 🦓👩🏻‍🎨 Honestly, I’ll never paint a room without this hack again — stripes or no stripes. PS. One obvious tip I forgot in the video: before painting, go over the tape with your finger or something round like a bottle cap to make sure it’s well-sealed to the wall. #DIY #painting #Stripes #wallpaper #interiors #interiordecor

node.text: Introducing a thing I’ll call “My Husband Fixing Things” 💁🏻‍♀️⚒️👷🏻‍♂️It’s not quite “Style Spy” but let’s give it a whirl. Plus! 📯A little personal news: we found an old 17th century water mill outside of Paris & liked it so much that we decided to put ourselves into debt for the next 1/4 of a century for it 🙃🏡 So as I follow him around the place discovering his hidden talents (so far we’ve got plumber, electrician, plasterer, solderer and woodchuck chucker 🐿), I thought maybe you guys might have some DIY-related questions that need answering! He doesn’t technically know I’ve signed him up for this but ... Ask us anything 😬💬🛠🪚🧰 #MyHusbandFixingThings #DIY  #MessyNessyMill

node.text: My book “Don’t be a Tourist in Paris” has a new home in the online brocante of @MadamedelaMaison 🥂 If you can’t make it to the Paris flea market, she’s bringing it to you 🕵🏾‍♀️ A master curator of household treasures, tireless Parisian antiques hunter, Nigerian-born mother of two, American-raised entrepreneur, Capricorn sister and dear friend🪆Every trinket in her shop has a story behind it. Go check it out & thank you for continuing to support small businesses 💛 📷: 📘 photographed & now available chez @madamedelamaison (and we’re always in stock for books in case you guys clear her out) 😉📚 #DontBeaTourist #books #supportsmallbusiness #Paris
